==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Perk
<hw>Perk</hw> <pr>(p⟦etil⟧rk)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Perked</conjf> <pr>(p⟦etil⟧rkt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Perking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. W.
<ets>percu</ets> to trim, to make smart.]</ety> <def>To make trim or
smart; to straighten up; to erect; to make a jaunty or saucy display of;
<as>as, to <ex>perk</ex> the ears; to <ex>perk</ex> up one's
head.</as></def> <rj><au>Cowper.</au> <au>Sherburne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>to perk up one's ears</b></col> <cd>to begin to listen
attentively; -- usually used when something of interest is mentioned in
some discourse, after one's attention had lapsed; <as>as, he <ex>perked
up his ears</ex> when he heard his name mentioned</as>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Perk</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Perk
<hw>Perk</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To exalt one's self; to
bear one's self loftily.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧To <xex>perk</xex> over
them.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Barrow.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To act in a jaunty or presumptuous manner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To perk it</b></col>, <cd>to carry one's self proudly or
saucily.</cd> <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Perk</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Perk
<hw>Perk</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Smart; trim; spruce; jaunty;
vain.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Perk</xex> as a peacock.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Perk</ent>⟦br⟧

